10
00:00:23,510 --> 00:00:26,330
The rumor mill is churning in Beijing!

11
00:00:26,330 --> 00:00:29,050
Word on the street is a coup attempt was launched

12
00:00:29,050 --> 00:00:31,890
against Chinese leader Xi Jinping.

13
00:00:31,890 --> 00:00:34,940
There were reports of gunfire near the heart
of the capital…

14
00:00:34,940 --> 00:00:38,370
...from anti-Xi groups trying to overthrow
him.

15
00:00:38,370 --> 00:00:41,180
But here’s where it gets really weird.

16
00:00:41,180 --> 00:00:43,860
The rumors say that black rain frog and former

17
00:00:43,860 --> 00:00:46,090
former Chinese leader Jiang Zemin,

18
00:00:46,090 --> 00:00:50,370
had teamed up with wood face and former leader
Hu Jintao

19
00:00:50,370 --> 00:00:52,650
to overthrow Xi Jinping.

20
00:00:52,650 --> 00:00:55,960
And THAT...is incredibly unlikely.

21
00:00:55,960 --> 00:00:56,960
Hu Jintao was the head

22
00:00:56,960 --> 00:01:00,390
of the Chinese Communist Party between Jiang
and Xi.

23
00:01:00,390 --> 00:01:01,860
Hu’s on first?

24
00:01:01,860 --> 00:01:03,100
Xi’s on first!

25
00:01:03,100 --> 00:01:06,050
Ok, now it’s just more confusing.

26
00:01:06,050 --> 00:01:09,420
But anyway, before Xi Jinping became the leader
of China,

27
00:01:09,420 --> 00:01:10,910
there was Hu Jintao.

28
00:01:10,910 --> 00:01:13,380
And before him, Jiang Zemin.

29
00:01:13,380 --> 00:01:16,540
And before him, Deng Xiaoping.

30
00:01:16,540 --> 00:01:18,790
Jiang Zemin was jealous that Hu Jintao

31
00:01:18,790 --> 00:01:21,210
got to become the leader after him,

32
00:01:21,210 --> 00:01:24,640
because Jiang didn’t get to pick his own
successor.

33
00:01:24,640 --> 00:01:28,030
So Jiang constantly tried to undermine Hu,

34
00:01:28,030 --> 00:01:32,420
and also possibly tried to kill him that one
time on a boat.

35
00:01:32,420 --> 00:01:36,400
Unfortunately for Jiang, he didn’t manage
to sink Hu’s battleship.

36
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:40,500
In any case, I think it’s safe to say Hu
Jintao did not team up

37
00:01:40,500 --> 00:01:43,730
with Jiang Zemin to overthrow Xi Jinping.

38
00:01:43,730 --> 00:01:47,810
But rumors can be a powerful force in Chinese
politics.

39
00:01:47,810 --> 00:01:51,140
“Given the Party’s control over the media
and the secretive

40
00:01:51,140 --> 00:01:53,479
nature of its political processes,

41
00:01:53,479 --> 00:01:55,740
gossip and rumours have long been the stuff

42
00:01:55,740 --> 00:01:58,760
of informal comment on the issues of the day,

43
00:01:58,760 --> 00:02:02,300
and the means by which alternative accounts
of Party rule circulate.”

44
00:02:02,300 --> 00:02:06,509
In fact, this latest incident isn’t even
the first time rumors

45
00:02:06,509 --> 00:02:09,929
of a coup against Xi Jinping have circulated.

46
00:02:09,929 --> 00:02:11,319
Shortly after Xi Jinping was appointed

47
00:02:11,319 --> 00:02:14,269
Chairman of the Communist Party in 2012,

48
00:02:14,269 --> 00:02:17,340
